	<h2>Education in Liberia Isn't Broken, It's Been Left Behind.</h2>
	<p>
		Across Liberia, students still sit on bare floors in overcrowded classrooms. Teachers, though dedicated, are often forced to teach with outdated textbooks, limited training, and no real support. Parents, who sacrifice greatly to send their children to school, quietly hope that effort alone will be enough. But too often, it's not.
	</p>
	<p>
		Even the most determined learners fall through the cracks, not for lack of intelligence, but for lack of access.
	</p>
	<p>
		<strong>We've lived this reality. And we've had enough.</strong>
	</p>

	<h2>The Turning Point</h2>
	<p>
		In November 2023, three of us, <strong>Massalan</strong>, a high school student who saw firsthand how the system fails learners like her; <strong>Faith</strong>, a peer equally driven to change things; and <strong>Boniface</strong>, a mentor who spent years guiding youth and watching their potential go untapped, met through the Liberia Diamond Challenge, a national innovation program backed by YONER Liberia and the University of Delaware.
	</p>
	<p>
		What brought us together wasn't just a competition, it was a shared frustration. A shared question:
	</p>
	<p>
		<strong>What if we could build what we never had?</strong>
	</p>

