	<h2>We Started Listening</h2>
	<p>
		We didn't begin by building tech.
	</p>
	<p>
		<strong>We began by listening.</strong>
	</p>
	<p>
		We spoke to students, teachers, parents, and working adults across the country. What we uncovered was both urgent and undeniable:
	</p>
	<h3>1. Too many students. Too few teachers.</h3>
	<p>One teacher to 60+ students makes personal learning impossible.</p>
	
	<h3>2. Textbooks from decades ago.</h3>
	<p>No access to modern tools, videos, or personalized help.</p>
	
	<h3>3. Tutoring is a luxury.</h3>
	<p>Only wealthier families can afford extra learning support.</p>
	
	<h3>4. Working adults are left out.</h3>
	<p>They want to learn, but flexible, affordable options are rare.</p>

	<h2>So We Built DUAHTOR</h2>
	<p>
		DUAHTOR is an app and a Liberian-built learning companion for students, educators, parents, and professionals.
	</p>
	<p>It offers:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>AI-powered tutoring</strong> that adapts to each learner's pace.</li>
		<li><strong>Assignment support</strong> that explains, not just solves.</li>
		<li><strong>A Super Reading Coach</strong> for literacy and fluency.</li>
		<li><strong>Offline access</strong> for areas with poor internet.</li>
		<li><strong>Professional courses</strong> to upskill working learners.</li>
		<li><strong>A resource vault</strong> for teachers, and</li>
		<li><strong>A dashboard</strong> for parents to stay involved.</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		We didn't build DUAHTOR in a boardroom, we built it in classrooms, homes, and conversations. It's rooted in reality, tested by real people, and guided by a mission we live daily.
	</p>

	<h2>The Road Hasn't Been Easy</h2>
	<p>
		Our journey hasn't been without setbacks.
	</p>
	<p>
		When we were invited to pitch DUAHTOR at the global finals in the U.S., a visa denial stopped us cold.
	</p>
	<p>
		When we tried to raise funds, doors closed, again and again.
	</p>
	<p>
		<strong>But we never stopped.</strong>
	</p>
	<p>
		Every "no" only confirmed why we're doing this. Because the need doesn't wait.
	</p>

	<h2>What Drives Us Now</h2>
	<p>
		We're not trying to build the next trendy app.
	</p>
	<p>
		We're trying to make sure that the next Massalan doesn't give up.
	</p>
	<p>
		That Faith's little sister doesn't fall behind just because she lives in a rural town.
	</p>
	<p>
		That a parent like Boniface can finally see real progress, not just school fees.
	</p>
	<p>
		<strong>This is personal.</strong><br>
		<strong>This is national.</strong><br>
		<strong>This is possible.</strong>
	</p>

